5 "§ 95-31.6. Notification, posting, and records.
6 Employers shall give notice (i) that employees are entitled to paid sick time, (ii) of the amount
7 of paid sick time and the terms of its use guaranteed under this section, (iii) that retaliation against
8 employees who request or use paid sick time is prohibited, and (iv) that each employee has the
9 right to file a complaint with the Commissioner of Labor or in the General Court of Justice if
10 paid sick time as required by this Article is denied by the employer or the employee is retaliated
11 against for requesting or taking paid sick time. Employers may comply with this section by
12 supplying each of their employees with a notice in English and in Spanish that contains the
13 information required by this section or by displaying a poster in a conspicuous and accessible
14 place in each establishment where the employees are employed that contains in English and in
15 Spanish all information required by this section.
16 "§ 95-31.7. Enforcement.
17 (a) The Commissioner shall enforce and administer the provisions of this Article, and the
18 Commissioner or his or her authorized representative is empowered to hold hearings and to
19 institute civil proceedings hereunder.
20 (b) The Commissioner or the Commissioner's authorized representative shall have power
21 to administer oaths and examine witnesses, issue subpoenas, compel the attendance of witnesses
22 and the production of papers, books, accounts, records, payrolls, and documents, and take
23 depositions and affidavits in any proceeding hereunder.
24 (c) Any employer who violates the provisions of this Article shall be liable to the
25 employee or employees affected in the amount of their unpaid sick time, as the case may be, plus
26 interest at the legal rate set forth in G.S. 24-1 from the date each amount first came due.
27 (d) In addition to the amounts awarded pursuant to subsection (c) of this section, the court
28 shall award liquidated damages in an amount equal to the amount found to be due as provided in
29 subsection (c) of this section, provided that if the employer shows to the satisfaction of the court
30 that the act or omission constituting the violation was in good faith and that the employer had
31 reasonable grounds for believing that the act or omission was not a violation of this Article, the
32 court may, in its discretion, award no liquidated damages or may award any amount of liquidated
33 damages not exceeding the amount found due as provided in subsection (c) of this section.
34 (e) Action to recover such liability may be maintained in the General Court of Justice by
35 any one or more employees.
36 (f) The court, in any action brought under this Article, may, in addition to any judgment
37 awarded to the plaintiff, order costs and fees of the action and reasonable attorneys' fees to be
38 paid by the defendant. The court may order costs and fees of the action and reasonable attorneys'
39 fees to be paid by the plaintiff if the court determines that the action was frivolous.
40 (g) The Commissioner may determine and supervise the payment of the amounts due
41 under this section, including interest at the legal rate set forth in G.S. 24-1 from the date each
42 amount first came due, and the agreement to accept such amounts by the employee shall
43 constitute a waiver of the employee's right to bring an action under subsection (e) of this section.
44 (h) Actions under this Article must be brought within two years pursuant to G.S. 1-53.
45 (i) The rights and remedies created by this Article are supplementary to all existing
46 common-law and statutory rights and remedies.
47 "§ 95-31.8. Rules.
48 The Commissioner of Labor shall adopt rules to implement this Article.
49 "§ 95-31.9. Severability.
