34 SECTION 1.4. Article 16 of Chapter 95 of the General Statutes is amended by
35 adding two new sections to read:
36 "§ 95-158. Workplace safety requirements.
37 (a) Heat Exposure Safety. – Each employer shall adopt a heat safety plan for employees
38 that, at a minimum, does all of the following:
39 (1) Provide workers with readily accessible drinking water.
40 (2) Establish and maintain shaded or climate-controlled rest areas.
41 (3) Implement mandatory rest periods during high-heat conditions.
42 (4) Develop and implement written heat illness prevention procedures.
43 (5) Provide heat safety training to workers and supervisors.
44 (6) Maintain records of heat-related incidents and prevention measures.
45 (7) Implement an acclimatization schedule for new workers and workers
46 returning after 30 or more consecutive days away.
47 When temperatures exceed 90 degrees Fahrenheit for more than 15 minutes during a
48 60-minute period, or where employees are performing a heavy workload or are required to wear
49 double-layer woven clothing, employers shall modify work schedules to minimize heat exposure,
50 increase rest frequency, establish a mandatory buddy system, and maintain communication
51 systems for heat-related emergency response.
DRS45160-LRfap-14G Page 7

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) Natural Disaster and Evacuation Safety. – Each employer shall adopt a safety plan in
2 the event of natural disaster or evacuation to provide for employee readiness, health, and safety.
3 (c) Rules. – The Commissioner of Labor shall adopt rules to implement this section.
4 "§ 95-159. Employee rights in an emergency.
5 (a) The following definitions apply in this section:
6 (1) Emergency condition. – The existence of either of the following:
7 a. Conditions of disaster or extreme peril to the safety of persons or
8 property at the workplace or worksite caused by natural forces or a
9 criminal act.
10 b. An order to evacuate a workplace, a worksite, a worker's home, or the
11 school of a worker's child due to natural disaster or a criminal act.
12 The term does not include a health pandemic.
13 (2) A reasonable belief that the workplace or worksite is unsafe. – When a
14 reasonable person, under the circumstances known to the employee at the
15 time, would conclude there is a real danger of death or serious injury if that
16 person enters or remains on the premises. The existence of any health and
17 safety regulations specific to the emergency condition and an employer's
18 compliance or noncompliance with those regulations shall be a relevant factor
19 if this information is known to the employee at the time of the emergency
20 condition or the employee received training on the health and safety
21 regulations mandated by law specific to the emergency condition.
22 (b) In the event of an emergency condition, an employer shall not:
23 (1) Take or threaten adverse action against any employee for refusing to report to,
24 or leaving, a workplace or worksite within the affected area because the
25 employee has a reasonable belief that the workplace or worksite is unsafe; or
26 (2) Prevent any employee from accessing the employee's mobile device or other
27 communications device for seeking emergency assistance, assessing the
28 safety of the situation, or communicating with a person to verify their safety.
29 (c) The provisions of subsection (b) of this section do not apply to any of the following:
30 (1) A first responder, disaster service worker, or any employee required by law to
31 render aid or remain on the premises in case of an emergency.
32 (2) An employee or contractor of a health care facility who provides direct patient
33 care, provides services supporting patient care operations during an
34 emergency, or is required by law or policy to participate in emergency
35 response or evacuation.
36 (3) An employee of a private entity that contracts with the State or a local political
37 subdivision of the State for purposes of providing or aiding in emergency
38 services.
39 (4) An employee working on a military base or in the defense industrial base
40 sector.
41 (5) An employee performing essential work on nuclear reactors or nuclear
42 materials or waste.
43 (6) An employee of a company providing utility, communications, energy, or
44 roadside assistance while the employee is actively engaged in or is being
45 called upon to aid in emergency response, including maintaining public access
46 to services such as energy and water during the emergency.
47 (7) An employee of a licensed residential care facility.
48 (8) An employee of a depository institution or any company within any of the
49 definitions of "insured depository institution" set forth in 12 U.S.C. § 1813(c).
50 (9) A transportation employee participating directly in emergency evacuations
51 during an active evacuation.
Page 8 DRS45160-LRfap-14G

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (10) An employee of a privately contracted private fire prevention resource.
2 (11) An employee whose primary duties include assisting members of the public
3 to evacuate in case of an emergency.
4 (12) An employee of any correctional facility.
5 (d) When feasible, an employee shall notify the employer of the emergency condition
6 requiring the employee to leave or refuse to report to the workplace or worksite prior to leaving
7 or refusing to report. When prior notice is not feasible, the employee shall notify the employer
8 of the emergency condition that required the employee to leave or refuse to report to the
9 workplace or worksite after leaving or refusing to report as soon as possible.
10 (e) This section does not to apply when emergency conditions that pose an imminent and
11 ongoing risk of harm to the workplace, the worksite, the worker, or the worker's home have
12 ceased.
13 (f) The Commissioner of Labor may bring an enforcement action under this section upon
14 a complaint by a current or former employee.
15 (g) The employee has a private right of action against an employer who violates this
16 section when the violation results in actual harm to the employee. The employer shall have the
17 right to cure alleged violations before any action by a current or former employee may be brought
18 under this section."
